awd_abstract_narration:
To best serve the growing national and global supply chain workforce environment, new talent must be engaged in programmatic opportunities to address the skills-gap in emerging technician occupations. The Valencia College Engineering Technology Supply Chain Automation ATE project located in Central Florida aims to advance research on effective practices in engineering technology (ET) workforce education through a new curriculum framework and innovative approaches to teaching supply chain automation (SCA). The need for the project was driven in consultation with the National Center of Supply Chain Automation and with input from nationally recognized regional employers who reinforced the national and regional labor shortage. The new SCA-specialization will seek to provide a model for community colleges across the country, contributing to a growing movement for businesses and industries to become more efficient in distribution and supply chain automation practices. As the first program offered in the state of Florida, working closely with local business, industry, civic, and government partners, the program plans to attract and graduate a diversity of students, including underrepresented minorities (URMs) and women, to the growing field of supply chain technician jobs. The project is designed to demonstrate that the SCA-specialization within the ET associate degree (A.S.) program is a viable two-year degree option that will serve the community through partnerships with industry, leading to high wage employment opportunities in high-demand occupations, and generating new knowledge on the skills and competencies identified by industry to meet the workforce needs in SCA. Following a rigorous evaluation, Valencia will share best practices, curriculum and insight with other ATE centers and projects and collaborators to add knowledge to benefit the whole. 

The project will support building a robust workforce within demographics that will impact the future vitality of the technically-trained workforce. Through a replicable model, the project aims to develop this new SCA-specialization and college certificate and offer rigorous technical courses that will be taught in creative ways, using approaches proven to engage all students. Project objectives are to (1) develop and implement the new specialization within the state ET associate degree curriculum framework; (2) provide professional development for faculty and secondary education teachers aimed at improving instructional practices and learning outcomes, and having faculty obtain industry-recognized credentials; and (3) collaborate with high schools to develop a pathway to the SCA specialization with evidenced-based teaching and learning practices that increase early awareness and exposure to ET pathways for a wide diversity of students. Project deliverables will target (a) increased industry connections, (b) the development of a new SCA-specialization and college certificate, (c) increased secondary education partnerships, (d)  professional development for a minimum of eight high school teachers a year who participate in the SCA trainings to learn best-practices on the engagement of URM and female students in ET pathways, and (e) faculty preparation for a minimum of four faculty who will complete the trainings to be prepared with the necessary skills and credentials to teach the SCA curriculum.

This award reflects NSF's statutory mission and has been deemed worthy of support through evaluation using the Foundation's intellectual merit and broader impacts review criteria.

por.por_cntn:
Manufacturing and Supply Chain is the fastest growing industry in the state of Florida. Valencia College Engineering Technology program with specialization in Supply Chain Automation (ET-SCA or ?the project?) aims to advance research on effective practices in engineering technology workforce education through a new curriculum framework and innovative approaches to teaching supply chain automation (SCA).

The major goal for this project was to provide access to advanced technology education that leads to higher-level employment opportunities for traditional and nontraditional student interested in pursuing a Supply Chain Automation-specialization within Engineering Technology (ET) Associate in Science (A.S) program.

The NSF project included three specific objectives:

1.      To develop SCA curriculum standards to be included in the currently approved curriculum frameworks at the Florida Department of Education as well as the required courses for the SCA specialization and several stackable College Credit Certificates (CCC) to foster an environment of learning and success through hands-on experiences.

2.      To provide professional development for faculty and secondary education teachers aimed at improving instructional practices and learning outcomes as well as obtaining industry-recognized credentials.

3.      To collaborate with Orange and Osceola County high schools to develop a pathway to the ET A.S. program with SCA specialization with evidenced-based practices that increase early awareness and exposure to engineering technology pathways for non-traditional female students and URM students.

To achieve the goals and objectives of the project, Valencia team first identified members to serve on the SCA Specialization Steering committee and the Project Advisory committees. The team also established three taskforce (curriculum, high- school instructor training, STEM outreach) groups with specific duties and responsibilities to assist with the work of the project. 

During the year 1 of the project, the team actively engaged and connected with the local industry partners to serve on the program Industry Advisory Committee (IAC) and participate in the curriculum development and DACUM focus group process and activities. Today, the program has 14 industry partners representing many supply chain industry from the college service area that are actively involved with the program curriculum, learning outcome, internships, and employment opportunities for the students.

CO-PI, Professor Ali Notash, conducted an extensive research, gathering wealth of information from variety institutions and organizations with similar programs and training. His work resulted in identifying and developing many courses aligned with the outcomes and recommendation of the DACUM focus group.

Professor Notash also used the result and outcomes of the DACUM to develop the SCA curriculum framework standards as well as four 12-31 credit stackable college credit certificates (Objective 1) as part of the Engineering Technology program. The project purchased the necessary equipment and software to support students with the hands-on experiments and projects.

In year 2, the project hired a full-time faculty. The faculty participated in several conferences, webinars, and workshops for professional development (Objective 2) and participated in teacher training workshop in supply chain automation delivered to several high school teachers. Co-PI MacDonald and Professor Kevin Curley presented the ET curriculum at the NCSCA symposium in Spring of 2020.

The project team working with the program faculty, conducted outreach activities, focusing on engineering occupations and pathways. With the support of Valencia?s transition team and the High School counselors, the faculty delivered one day STEM camp (Objective 3) focusing on manufacturing/engineering technician training to over 25 students from district high schools at Valencia Advanced Manufacturing Center. In January 2022, the program conducted a CTE camp for 30 district high school students pursing STEM programs.  

As of May 2022, the Engineering Technology program equipped with the state-of-the-art equipment has one tenure track faculty, several part-time faculty, and one dedicated career program advisor.

There are currently 203 declared student majors taking classes in face-to-face, online, or Real Time Virtual (RTV) modalities. Student characteristics data shows 80% are male and 17% female with 35% being first generation students enrolled in classes with part-time (60%) or full-time (40%) status.

Engineering Technology program is a welcoming learning environment to over 48% Hispanic students followed by 22% Caucasian and 12% African American students.

For more program information please visit:

https://net1.valenciacollege.edu/future-students/degree-options/associates/engineering-technology/
